{tt|ga|eachra|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt|nb|kavallerist|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|cavalaria|f}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|cavaler}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|jazda|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|caballería|f}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|atlı}}, {{tt+|tr|süvari}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|ئاتلىق ئەسكەر}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt+|zza|aspar|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|gymnastic equipment}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|նժույգ}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|кон|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|poltre|m}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|kůň|m}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|bok}}\n* Faroese: {{tt+|fo|hestur|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|hevonen}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|cheval d'arçons|m}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|cabalería|f}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Pferd|n}}, {{tt+|de|Pauschenpferd|n}}, {{tt+|de|Seitpferd|n}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|ίππος|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|ló}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|hestur|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|cavallina|f}}, {{t+|it|cavallo|m}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|amorangi}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|hest|m}}, {{tt+|nb|bukk|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|cavalo|m}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|capră}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|конь|m}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|potro|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|bock}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|kasa}}, {{tt+|tr|beygir}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|ياغاچ ئات}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|frame with legs used for support or for holding objects}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|магаре|n}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|cavallet|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|cavalletto|m}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|kaupae}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ко́злы|m-p}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|caballete|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-also|knight in chess|knight}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|perd}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|кон|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|cavall|m}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|говр}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|馬|tr=mǎ}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|kůň|m}}, {{tt+|cs|jezdec|m}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|paard|n}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|ratsu}}, {{tt|et|hobu}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|riddari|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|ratsu}}, {{tt+|fi|hevonen}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|cavalier}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|cabalo|m}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Springer|m}}, {{tt+|de|Pferd|n}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|ίππος}}, {{tt+|el|άλογο|n}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|פָּרָשׁ|m|tr=parash}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|घोड़ा|m}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|riddari|m}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|kuda}}\n* Javanese: {{tt+|jv|jaran}}\n* Kashmiri: {{tt+|ks|گُر|m}}\n* Khmer: {{tt+|km|សេះ}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|kuda}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt|nb|springer|m}}, {{tt+|nb|hest|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|cavalo|m}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|cal}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|конь|m}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|caballo|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|springare|c}}, {{tt+|sv|häst|c}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|ม้า}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|at}}\n* Turkmen: {{tt+|tk|at}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|گھوڑا|m}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt+|ug|ئات}}\n* Zazaki: {{t+|zza|bergir|m}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{col|en|title=Related terms\n|knight,cavalier,cavalry,chivalry\n|equid,equine\n|gee,haw,giddy-up,whoa\n|hoof,mane,tail,withers\n|gallop,canter,walk,trot\n|neigh,whinny\n|tandem,team,chariot,cart,wagon\n|ungulate\n}}\n{{table:xiangqi pieces/en}}\n* [[:Category:en:Horses|Horse-related English words]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|horsen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|horsian|t=to horse, provide with horses}} and {{m|ang|ġehorsian|t=to horse, set or mount on a horse, supply with horses}}, from the noun (see above).\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} {{syn of|en|horse around}}.\n#: {{syn|en|horse about|horse around}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1958|author=Gay Gaer Luce|title=Cross Your Heart|page=181\n|passage=\"Stop '''horsing''', and guess how many kids!\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2019|author=Frank Kane|title=Red Hot Ice: A Johnny Liddell Mystery|page=117\n|passage=\"Why don't we stop '''horsing''' and get down to cases, Lou?\" Mike Davey growled.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To play mischievous pranks on.\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2015-03-07|author=Cornelius Vanderbilt Jr.|title=Palm Beach: A Novel|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781590775134|page=106\n|text=Was someone '''horsing''' her? Was it Josh's idea of a joke? For some moments she sat, plump hands with long pointed pink nails, toying with the envelope. Then she went to the telephone and called{{nb...}}}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[provide]] with a horse; [[supply]] horses for.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 4-2|I|i|passage=being better '''horsed''', outrode me}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1907|title=Cavalry Journal\n|text={{...}} and the same number from Russia for '''horsing''' her guns. During peace Turkey has 15,000 regular Cavalry; on mobilisation she should have 21,000, and 4,000 pack animals, without taking the irregular corps into consideration.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1887|author=Harriet W. Daly|title=Digging, Squatting, and Pioneering Life in the Northern Territory of South Australia|page=303|passage=The result of one night's play was that the man who '''horsed''' the party had not one hoof to call his own when the morning's reckoning came to be made.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To get on horseback.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1888|author=w:Rudyard Kipling|title=s:Cupid's Arrows\n|passage=''He '''horsed''' himself well.''}}\n# To sit astride of; to bestride.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Cymbeline|II|i|line=203|text=Stalls, bulks, windows / Are smothered up, leads filled, and ridges '''horsed''' / With variable complexions, all agreeing / In earnestness to see him.}}\n# {{lb|en|of a male horse}} To [[copulate]] with (a [[mare]]).\n# To take or carry on the back.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=c. 1667|author=w:Samuel Butler|title=Characters\n|passage=keepers, '''horsing''' the deer}}\n# To place (someone) on the back of another person, or on a wooden horse, chair, etc., to be [[flog]]ged or punished.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1963|author=Charles Harold Nichols|title=Many Thousand Gone| passage=So they brought him out and '''horsed''' him upon the back of Planter George, and whipped him until he fell quivering in the dust.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2020-04-02|author=Toby Neal|title=Paradise Crime Mysteries Books 1-9|publisher=Neal Enterprises INC\n|text=Faster than Lei could have believed, Omura blocked the exit, grabbed Kennedy's wrist and twisted it up behind her back, '''horsing''' her onto the hard metal chair. She sat the woman on it, slapping on a pair of cuffs.}}\n## {{lb|en|by extension}} To [[flog]].\n##* {{RQ:Smollett Peregrine Pickle|volume=I|20|text=[N]otwithstanding the intercession of his governor, who begged earnestly that his punishment might be mitigated, our unfortunate hero was publickly '''horsed''', ''in terrorem'' of all whom it might concern.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To pull, haul{{,}} or move (something) with great effort, like a [[#Noun|horse]] would.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1836|author=Hugh Murray; John Crawfurd; Peter Gordon; Thomas Lynn; William Wallace; Gilbert Thomas Burnett|title=An Historical and Descriptive Account of China|page=216\n|text=[A] country-ship from China to Bombay, standing into the strait at noon with a strong tide and scant wind, stood too near Pedro Branco before tacking, and was totally lost, by the tide '''horsing''' her upon the rock whilst in stays.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1870|title=Hunt's Yachting Magazine|page=266\n|text=Cambria observing this again went about, and tacked towards the island, Sappho followed suit; after a short reach she again tacked and stood for the mark vessel, the tide '''horsing''' her well to the westward, but the Cambria stood on{{nb...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1981|author=Robert Roderick|title=The Greek Position: A Novel|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=9780671610159\n|text=At 2:30 P.M. two gray-and-yellow tugs began '''horsing''' her out of her berth. Backing, she turned to starboard, past the end of the dock. Engine stopped, she carried sternway as her bow swung for the harbor mouth.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal}} To [[cram]] (food) quickly, indiscriminately or in great volume.<!--improve def?-->\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2012-02-02|author=Anna Smith|title=To Tell the Truth: Rosie Gilmour 2|publisher=Quercus Publishing|isbn=9780857384249\n|text=The Spaniards spend generations honing the subtle flavours of their delightful tapas and you're '''horsing''' it into your mouth as though it was a fried egg roll with brown sauce.'}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2021-01-07|author=Paul Olima|title=Fit: Smash your goals and stay strong for life|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781471197529\n|text=Get your laughing gear around some protein at every meal, spreading your intake over the course of the day rather than '''horsing''' it into you all in one go, at one mealtime. If you are training hard, try to consume around 25g protein{{nb...}} }}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|dated}} To urge at work tyrannically.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|dated}} To charge for work before it is finished.\n# {{lb|en|dated|slang}} To [[cheat]] at schoolwork by means of a translation or other illegitimate aid.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|horse about}}\n* {{l|en|horse around}}\n* {{l|en|unhorse}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to frolic}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|dovádět|impf}}, {{t+|cs|blbnout|impf}}, {{t|cs|dělat vylomeniny|impf}}, {{t|cs|dělat koniny|impf}}, {{t|cs|dělat blbiny|impf}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|pelleillä}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|atast}}, {{t|is|fíflast}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to provide with a horse}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[varustaa]] [[hevosella]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{unk|en}}; probably originally criminals' [[cant]] based on the initial letter of {{m|en|heroin}} and {{m|en|horse#Etymology 1}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|-}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|heroin}} {{lb|en|slang}} [[heroin|Heroin]] {{gloss|drug}}.\n#: {{syn|en|H|smack|Thesaurus:heroin}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=13-09-1957|title=The Cherubs Are Rumbling|author={{w|Walter Bernstein}}|journal=The New Yorker|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1957/09/21/the-cherubs-are-rumbling|archiveurl=https://archive.is/dvaQb|archivedate=2024-02-18|volume=|issue=|page=|text=Riccio nodded toward a boy across the floor and said, “See that kid? He’s on dope.” The boy was standing against a wall, staring vacantly at the dancers, his face fixed in a gentle, faraway smile. Every few seconds, he would wipe his nose with the back of his hand.<br/>“Man, that Jo-Jo!” Benny said. “He’s stoned all the time.”<br/>“What’s he on—'''horse'''? Riccio asked, meaning heroin.<br/>“Who knows with that creep?” Benny said. I asked Benny if any special kind of boy went in for dope.<br/>“The creeps,” he said. “You know, the goofballs.” He searched for a word. “The weak kids. Like Jo-Jo. There ain’t nothing the guys can’t do to him. Last week, we took his pants off and made him run right in the middle of the street without them.”}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1962|title=[[w:Cape Fear (1962 film)|Cape Fear]]|section=00:15:20\n|passage=Check that shirt. I got a couple of [[jolt]]s of '''horse''' stashed under the collar}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1962|year_published=1963|month_published=January|author=w:James Baldwin|title={{w|Another Country (novel)|Another Country}}|location=New York, N. Y.|publisher=w:The Dial Press|page=6|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/anothercountry0000bald/page/6/mode/2up?q=horse|passage=It was to remember the juke box, the teasing, the dancing, the hard-on, the gang fights and gang bangs, his first set of drums—bought him by his father—his first taste of marijuana, his first snort of '''horse'''.}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|sv|horse|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|slang: heroin}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|白麵兒|tr=báimiànr}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hepo}}, {{t+|fi|polle}}\n* Japanese: {{t-check|ja|ペー|tr=pē}}, {{t-check|ja|チャイナホワイト|tr=chainahowaito}}, {{t-check|ja|ジャンク|tr=janku}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|cavalo|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|cal|m}}, {{t|ro|cal alb|m}}, {{t+|ro|căluț|m}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|Ге́ра|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|caballo|m}}, {{t+|es|chiva|f}} {{qualifier|slang, Mexico}}, {{t|es|polvo blanco|m|lit=white powder}} {{q|euphemistic}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|horse}}, {{t+|sv|häst|c}}, {{t+|sv|jonk|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====Further reading=====\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{pedia|wild horse}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ehors|hoers|rohes|shoer|shero|shore|heros|hoser|Shore|RSeOH|Rohes}}\n\n{{C|en|Equids|Heroin|Horse racing|Horses|People}}\n{{cln|en|autohyponyms}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|hors}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|enm|adjective|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|hos}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|enm|verb|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|horsen|t=to provide with a horse|id=to provide with a horse}}\n\n{{c|enm|Equids|Horses}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Noun===\n{{nn-noun-f2}}\n\n# a [[mare]]\n# {{lb|nn|derogatory}} [[frivolous]] [[woman]]\n\n===Verb===\n{{nn-verb-1}}\n\n# {{lb|nn|intransitive|of a [[stallion]]}} to [[run]] [[around]] amongst the [[mare]]s\n# {{lb|nn|intransitive|of a [[man]]}} to run around, chiefly [[drunkenly]]\n\n{{C|nn|Horses}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|horse}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ang|noun form}}\n\n# {{infl of|ang|hors||dat|sg}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sco|enm|hors}}, {{m|enm|horse}}, from {{inh|sco|ang|hors}}, from {{inh|sco|gmw-pro|*hross}}, from {{inh|sco|gem-pro|*hrussą}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sco-noun|horse}}\n\n# {{l|en|horse}}\n#* {{RQ:Lorimer New Testament|book=Revelation|chapter=6|verse=8|page=426|passage=An I luikit, an thair afore my een wis a pailie '''horse''', an the name o its rider wis Deith. The Lord of the Gane-Awà Laund gaed at his side, an pouer wis gíen them tae fell wi the swuird an faimin an the pest, an bi the wild baists o the yird.|t=And I looked, and in front of my eyes there was a pale '''horse''', and the name of its rider was Death. The Lord of the Underworld went alongside him, and power was given to them to kill using the sword, famine, plague, and the Earth's wildlife.}}\n\n==Swedish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|sv|en|horse|id=heroin|t=heroin}}. {{doublet|sv|kärra|russ}}; related to {{m|sv|karriär}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|sv|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|sv|slang}} {{l|en|horse}} (heroin)\n#: {{syn|sv|häst|jonk|q2=brown heroin}}\n\n===References===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20211002212732/https://polisen.se/contentassets/834bec2316d242369ba652cabd01f7b9/har-du-koll-pa-drogslangen.pdf/download/ Swedish Police Authority list of drug slang]\n* [http://www.slangopedia.se/ordlista/?ord=horse Slangopedia]\n\n{{C|sv|Recreational drugs}}"}}